About
Aerobus is the official shuttle bus that connects Barcelona Airport (terminals 1 & 2) to Barcelona's city center. Every 5 minutes, 24 hours, 365 days a year in just 35 minutes. Along the route the bus stops at several important points of the city: Pla√ßa Espanya, Gran Via-Urgell, Placa Universitat and Pla√ßa Catalunya. Faster. More frequent. Economical. WiFi and USB charge onboard.
Duration: < 1 hour

Neighborhood: Eixample
Passing through the glorious Pla√ßa Catalunya, you enter the newer city district of Eixample, literally translated as ‚Äúextension,‚Äù which immediately becomes recognizable by its more spacious streets and elegant atmosphere. The main artery of this sizable district, Passeig de Gracia, is lined with high-end international designer stores. Not to be outdone, the glitz and glamour of this zone is perhaps best exemplified by the comfortable and lavish five-star hotels that flank the divine and modernistic buildings from some of the world‚Äôs most recognized architects such as Gaudi and Montaner.

    It's great, but be prepared for details.
    It's great, but be prepared for details. As others noted , if you arrive at T2 it's a bit of a hike to the bus and it is not signposted inside the building. Outside you'll see huge signs, and eventually you'll realize that the one the Aerobus is at is WAY down there. The bus is fine. We got off at Espanya, but you'll probably have similar results at the other stops. Each place is a HUGE circle, and if you're connecting to the Metro, only ONE point on the circle has a lift. Without that, you're schlepping suitcases down stairs, along a LOT of corridors, up stairs, down stairs .... Returning to the airport we just took a cab to Espanya. You're saving so much by taking the bus that it's money well spent.

    A Cultural Feast
    Being an Art lover, Barcelona was always going to be a treat, with its many museums and galleries, particularly leaning towards the contemporary. After much thought, we decide to purchase Barcelona Cards, which gave us free transport on the Metro, Busses and local trains. (with certain exclusions such as the Aerobus) as well as free admission to many of the museums. We picked up our cards in the airport terminal and travelled to our hotel on La Rambla by the Metro which has stations at the airport. Our hotel on La Rambla was well equipped, but just a warning; The metro run the length of La Rambla underneath the road. As a train passes, the road vibrates, as do the hotels. Be wary if you are a light sleeper though they finish about midnight to start again about 4.50am. More of a concern was the liveliness of La Rambla itself, with noise coming from the street throughout the night. Our room faced the street and this did cause some problems. On the whole, Barcelona is an amazing city with plenty for all. take time to look at what your preferences are because you will not be able to do everything.

    The Aerobus is an incredibly convenient and inexpensive way to get to the center of Barcelona and from there back to the airport. Avoid. Metro more reliable.
Oct 2024 ‚Ä¢ Family
On way into city centre, all passengers thrown off bus at Espanya due to planned industrial action. No mention of this during booking, no attempt to explain what was going on or how to find alternative route (which was not funded.) Quite scary tbh. Lots of shouting.

On way out of city centre, waited for 50 minutes at Catalunya...until Aerobus employee advised needed to go to Espanya due to cycling event. Again: no information in advance, huge (avoidable) delay in providing information about lack of service.

So no, they don't provide the 24/7 regular service advertised.

Do yourself a favour: avoid Aerobus if you intend to buy a Hola Barcelona ticket (which you can use to take the Metro to the centre instead).

THE way to get to and from the airport in Barcelona!!
May 2024 ‚Ä¢ Couples
Three cheers plus for Barcelona for providing one of the best transport services to and from the airport of any major city in the world! The Aerobus is super convenient, with it's downtown terminus at Placa de Catalunya (with a couple of other stops along the way). There are separate buses for Terminal 1 and Terminal 2, both loading and unloading at the east side of the plaza. Passengers can buy tickets in advance online or from machines, from staff nearby, or from the driver, and can pay with credit card. The buses have lots of space for luggage. The trip to or from the airport takes less than 30 minutes and there are buses running every 10 minutes or less. The fare is 7.25 euros. If traveling from the airport, you may need to ask staff where to get the Aerobus, but it is easy to locate and everyone knows about it.T
